│ The current implementation of the poison check for commutative subtraction    │
│ patterns in `isKnownNegation` is overly restrictive. It assumes that both     │
│ operands of the subtraction must be constants and null values, which is not   │
│ always the case. This could lead to false negatives, where valid              │
│ transformations are rejected.                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ I will refine the poison check to ensure it correctly handles cases where the │
│ operands are not constants, while still ensuring that poison is not           │
│ introduced. Let me update the code accordingly.                               │
